VLia Addadi started her career with studies on fundamental principles of stereochemistry in crystals. She carved her special niche at the interfaces between hard and soft biological materials, studying the mechanisms of biomineralization, cell adhesion, and antibody recognition of organized materials. Her fundamental work has implications in areas as diverse as materials research, optics and medicine, including pathologies related to crystals, such as atherosclerosis and osteoporosis. Born in Padova, Italy, she obtained a Laurea (MSc) in Chemistry from the University of Padova, and a PhD from the Weizmann Institute of Science in Rehovot, Israel. After a postdoctoral period at Harvard she came back to the Weizmann Institute where she joined the Faculty of Chemistry in 1983. She was Head of the Department of Structural Biology, Dean of the Faculty of Chemistry and Dean of the Feinberg Graduate School. She is the recipient of numerous prizes, including the Prelog Medal in Stereochemistry (1998), the 2009 Prize for Excellence from the Israel Chemical Society, and the 2011 Aminoff Prize for Crystallography by the Swedish Royal Academy of Sciences.Lia Addadi started her career with studies on fundamental principles of stereochemistry in crystals. She carved her special niche at the interfaces between hard and soft biological materials, studying the mechanisms of biomineralization, cell adhesion, and antibody recognition of organized materials. Her fundamental work has implications in areas as diverse as materials research, optics and medicine, including pathologies related to crystals, such as atherosclerosis and osteoporosis. Born in Padova, Italy, she obtained a Laurea (MSc) in Chemistry from the University of Padova, and a PhD from the Weizmann Institute of Science in Rehovot, Israel. After a postdoctoral period at Harvard she came back to the Weizmann Institute where she joined the Faculty of Chemistry in 1983. She was Head of the Department of Structural Biology, Dea