VHelen Blau is a scientific pioneer in the field of stem cell biology and regenerative medicine. She is renowned for her research on nuclear reprogramming which demonstrated the plasticity of cell fate decades ago. Blau was born in London, England and grew up in Europe. She received her B.A. from the University of York, England in 1969, her Ph.D. from Harvard University in 1975, and was a postdoctoral fellow at UCSF. She joined the faculty at Stanford University in 1978 and is now the Donald E. and Delia B. Baxter Foundation Professor and Director of the Baxter Laboratory for Stem Cell Biology at Stanford University School of Medicine. She served as President of the American Society for Developmental Biology and President of the International Society of Differentiation. Awards include: Senior Career Recognition Women in Cell Biology Award, American Society of Cell Biology; Yvette Mayent-Rothschild Professorship; Nobel Forum Lecturer, Karolinska Institut; FASEB Excellence in Science Award; McKnight Innovations Award; Honorary Doctorate, University of Nijmegen; Member, Harvard Board of Overseers; AACR-Irving Weinstein Foundation Distinguished Lecturer. She is a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science and member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the National Academy of Medicine, and the National Academy of Sciences.Helen Blau is a scientific pioneer in the field of stem cell biology and regenerative medicine. She is renowned for her research on nuclear reprogramming which demonstrated the plasticity of cell fate decades ago. Blau was born in London, England and grew up in Europe. She received her B.A. from the University of York, England in 1969, her Ph.D. from Harvard University in 1975, and was a postdoctoral fellow at UCSF. She joined the faculty at Stanford University in 1978 and is now the Donald E. and Delia B. Baxter Foundation Professor and Director of the Baxter Laboratory for Stem Cell Biology at Stanford University Schoo