V"As a developmental biologist, I am interested in how a differentiated tissue forms from naive cells during embryonic development. Using mouse molecular genetics, I have focussed on the formation of skeletal and cardiac muscle. We first studied contractile protein genes, and then investigated the upstream gene hierarchies that control the onset of skeletal myogenesis. We have shown that Pax genes are key regulators, both of this cell fate choice in multipotent stem cells and in the subsequent activation of determination genes, such as Myf5, required for entry into the myogenic programme. Our studies on skeletal muscle extend to regeneration in the adult, where we have demonstrated the major role of the muscle satellite cell in response to injury or degenerative disease. Our work on cardiac muscle centers on regulation of the second heart field which we had identified in the mouse embryo as a major source of cells that form the myocardium at the poles of the heart. This finding was complemented by our characterisation of a second myocardial cell lineage, distinct from the first lineage that mainly gives rise to left ventricular myocardium. Recently we have established the lineage relationships between the venous and arterial poles of the heart, with implications for human congenital malformations.""As a developmental biologist, I am interested in how a differentiated tissue forms from naive cells during embryonic development. Using mouse molecular genetics, I have focussed on the formation of skeletal and cardiac muscle. We first studied contractile protein genes, and then investigated the upstream gene hierarchies that control the onset of skeletal myogenesis. We have shown that Pax genes are key regulators, both of this cell fate choice in multipotent stem cells and in the subsequent activation of determination genes, such as Myf5, required for entry into the myogenic programme. Our studies on skeletal muscle extend to regeneration in the adult, where we have demo