VMy research involves understanding the molecular genetic basis of human disease, running the gamut from Mendelian to oligogenic to complex, using experimental, quantitative and animal model approaches.  My laboratory  has made fundamental contributions to studies of polymorphism and linkage disequilibrium, both their biology and as tools for trait mapping.  These mapping studies, including GWAS (genome-wide association studies) required our collaborative development of genotyping technology (with Affymetrix) and computational methods for genome-wide screens. We pioneered GWAS in autism, hypertension and sudden cardiac death, revealing a diversity of novel genes contributing to their genetics. We also have a long history of studying the population genetics of deleterious alleles in isolated communities (Old Order Mennonites, Arab Israeli villages). Of these, the most significant and continuous effort has gone towards the genetic dissection and functional understanding of Hirschsprung disease, a model complex disorder where we have made fundamental and substantive contributions to understanding how mutations in genes specifying early neural crest-derived enteroblasts and their interaction with the gut mesenchyme led to this disorder of gut innervation. In a separate role, I have been one of the leading proponents and participants in the Human Genome (Chair, Subcommittee on IIIrd 5-year Genome Project Plan, NHGRI, NIH), HapMap (Steering Committee; Co-Chair Analysis Committee), and, 1000 Genomes Projects (Steering Committee; Co-Chair Samples & ELSI Committee) (see complete bibliography).My research involves understanding the molecular genetic basis of human disease, running the gamut from Mendelian to oligogenic to complex, using experimental, quantitative and animal model approaches.  My laboratory  has made fundamental contributions to studies of polymorphism and linkage disequilibrium, both their biology and as tools for trait mapping.  These mapping studies, includ