VEdward De Robertis is the Norman Sprague Professor of Biological Chemistry at the David Geffen School of Medicine at UCLA and an Investigator of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute. He is a developmental biologist recognized for his work demonstrating that a common genetic tool-kit regulates antero-posterior and dorsal-ventral cell differentiation in the embryos of all bilateral animals. De Robertis was born in Boston, Mass., and raised in Uruguay since age three, where he completed M.D. studies. This was followed by a Ph.D. in Chemistry at the Leloir Institute in Buenos Aires, Argentina. His postdoctoral training was in Cambridge, England, under renowned embryologist Sir John Gurdon. Following three years as staff member at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology, De Robertis was appointed full Professor at the University of Basel, Switzerland. Since 1985 he has been at UCLA. De Robertis is a member of the Pontifical Academy of Sciences, the Latin American Academy of Sciences, the European Molecular Biology Organization, and a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences. He received the Ross G. Harrison Prize in Developmental Biology, and a Honoris Causa doctorate from the Universités Sorbonne in Paris.Edward De Robertis is the Norman Sprague Professor of Biological Chemistry at the David Geffen School of Medicine at UCLA and an Investigator of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute. He is a developmental biologist recognized for his work demonstrating that a common genetic tool-kit regulates antero-posterior and dorsal-ventral cell differentiation in the embryos of all bilateral animals. De Robertis was born in Boston, Mass., and raised in Uruguay since age three, where he completed M.D. studies. This was followed by a Ph.D. in Chemistry at the Leloir Institute in Buenos Aires, Argentina. His postdoctoral training was in Cambridge, England, under renowned embryologist Sir John Gurdon. Following three years as staff member at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular B