VJim Dumesic is currently the Steenbock Chair in the College of Engineering and the Michel Boudart Professor of Chemical and Biological Engineering. Dumesic is widely recognized as a leading researcher in the fields of catalysis and chemical engineering. Throughout his career, Dumesic has used spectroscopic, microcalorimetric, and reaction kinetics techniques to study the surface and dynamic properties of heterogeneous catalysts. He pioneered the field of microkinetic analysis, in which diverse information from experimental and theoretical studies is combined to elucidate the essential surface chemistry that controls catalyst performance. His recent research has involved the catalytic conversion of renewable sources of lignocellulosic biomass to produce fuels and chemicals. Dumesic has co-founded two companies based on processes that this group has developed for creating bio-derived fuels and chemicals. Dumesic earned his B.S. degree from UW-Madison and his M.S. and Ph.D. degrees from Stanford University, under the supervision of Professor Michel Boudart. Dumesic joined the Department of Chemical Engineering at UW-Madison in 1976. He is a member of the National Academy of Engineering, the National Academy of Inventors, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and the National of Sciences. He has received awards from the American Institute of Chemical Engineers (Colburn Award, Wilhelm Award, Walker Award), the American Chemical Society (Somorjai Award, Olah Award), the North American Chemical Society (Emmett Award, Burwell Award, Boudart Award), and the International Association of Catalysis Societies (Heinemann Award).Jim Dumesic is currently the Steenbock Chair in the College of Engineering and the Michel Boudart Professor of Chemical and Biological Engineering. Dumesic is widely recognized as a leading researcher in the fields of catalysis and chemical engineering. Throughout his career, Dumesic has used spectroscopic, microcalorimetric, and reaction kinetics te