VThe Edwards lab wishes to understand how the basic properties of neurotransmitter release influence synaptic transmission and plasticity, behavior and neuropsychiatric disease. Using selection in a toxin that causes parkinsonism, they identified the first transporter that packages a classical transmitter into synaptic vesicles, implicating this activity in neural degeneration. The vesicular monoamine transporter defined a family of proteins that includes the vesicular acetylcholine transporter and the Edwards lab subsequently identified two other unrelated families that transport GABA and glutamate into synaptic vesicles. They also developed methods to elucidate the function, mechanism and regulation of these intracellular transporters. Using electrophysiology, they have shown that the vesicular glutamate transporters undergo an unusual form of allosteric regulation by Cl- and H+, and also exhibit an uncoupled Cl- conductance. Current work focuses on the role of these properties in glutamatergic neurotransmission. Since the vesicular transporters define the cells and vesicles capable of transmitter release, the group has also used them to establish the phenomenon of neurotransmitter corelease, in which a single neuron releases two classical transmitters. In addition, they have used targeting of the vesicular monoamine transporter to dense core vesicles to elucidate formation of the regulated secretory pathway that mediates release of peptide hormones and neural peptides. The work has diverse implications for behavior and disease, and Robert Edwards focuses on the pathogenesis of Parkinson\u2019s disease, in particular the function of the presynaptic protein alpha-synuclein that has a central role in this disorder.The Edwards lab wishes to understand how the basic properties of neurotransmitter release influence synaptic transmission and plasticity, behavior and neuropsychiatric disease. Using selection in a toxin that causes parkinsonism, they identified the first 